# **Introduction** {#introduction}

	Hello, thank you for your interest in the Server 2019 Administrator’s course. I’m Steve, the designer and instructor for this course.   
A little about me, I’ve been in information technology for the better part of twenty (20) years. Over the course of my IT career, I have worked directly or as a contractor for companies like Raytheon, Cessna, Metlife, and Royal Caribbean. For the last several years’ I’ve worked for a small consulting company managing all aspects of client’s Microsoft Server installations. I’ve performed multiple migrations to new versions of Microsoft Server where I was responsible for the design, migration, and ongoing maintenance of those installations. I have personally seen a drop of eighty percent (80%) or more reduction in server support calls from clients after I’ve gone in and upgraded their server environments.   
In this course, I will be sharing my real “in the trenches” experience with you. Hopefully making your life as a server administrator far less stressful. With this course, I wanted to fill in knowledge gaps that I’ve found so frustrating in YouTube videos, and blog posts, where they appear to simply rehash the Technet articles. I want you to have a better understanding of how things work in Microsoft Server, and how you can make things like migrations far easier on yourself going forward. To include some of the training for this course, we are going to start by creating a Server 2012 domain. So in the beginning of this course, you’re going to get a heavy dose of Server 2012 R2. Most of the topics covered in the creation of the lab will carry directly over to Server 2016\.  
So we’re going to look at the duties a real life server administrator would perform from migration to daily management, using the same implementations I build for my clients on a regular basis. It is my hope that everyone from novice to seasoned pro can learn something new from this course.

### **Hyper-V**

Microsoft’s Hyper-V has come a long way since it was first introduced. It’s still my go to for a virtual lab on my system. However, you can only use Hyper-V if you have certain enditions of either Windows 10 or 11, none of those are the Home Edition of Windows which is what most people are going to have installed.  

There is supposedly a way to install Hyper-V on Windows Home Edition, but it is not officially supported by Microsoft so I won’t be going into that. 

If you are using either the Pro, Education, or Enterprise edition of Windows 10 you can add Hyper-V provided you meet the hardware requirements which include a 64-bit processor with second level address translation, CPU support for VMs, and a minimum of 4GB of system RAM. 

Windows 11 requires either the Pro or Enterprise edition, plus the Windows 10 hardware requirements plus BIOS-level hardware virtualization support. 

#### Install Hyper-V (Windows 10\) {#install-hyper-v-(windows-10)}

[Enable Hyper-V on Windows 10 | Microsoft Learn](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/quick-start/enable-hyper-v)  
[Step-By-Step: Enabling Hyper-V for Use on Windows 11 (microsoft.com)](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/educator-developer-blog/step-by-step-enabling-hyper-v-for-use-on-windows-11/ba-p/3745905)

Before we can start building our lab, we need to install Hyper-V on our computer. If you’ve already turned the Hyper-V feature on, feel free to skip the section that’s appropriate for you. You can use the graphical interface (GUI) to turn the Hyper-V feature on, or you can use Powershell, use whichever way you prefer. 

***Note:*** You will only need to Install/Enable the Hyper-V feature if you are completing this lab on a Windows 10 workstation. If you are using a virtualized server to build the lab, you will not need to complete this.

##### GUI Method {#gui-method}

1. Open the Control Panel.  
2. Click on Programs.  
3. Click on Turn Windows features on or off.  
4. If unchecked, click on the box next to Hyper-V.  
5. Verify that both Hyper-V Management Tools and Hyper-V platform and sub options all have check marks in them. Note, you might see a black box in the Hyper-V platform, in which case, you want to be certain there are checks in the Hyper-V Hypervisor, and Hyper-V Services boxes under it.  
6. Click OK.  
7. Restart the computer as needed once the feature has been turned on.   
8. Open the Hyper-V Manager.

## **Creating virtual switches** {#creating-virtual-switches}

The first thing we want to do with the Hyper-V manager open is create a couple of virtual switches for our VMs to use. You can open the Virtual Switch Manager from the action pane, or by right-clicking on the local computer name and selecting the Virtual Switch Manager. I typically turn off the action pane as it only adds clutter to the window. 

There should already be a Default Switch that was created when you turned on the Hyper-V feature. Microsoft made several changes to the functionality of the default switch with the 1709, and 1803 updates, so you might see some odd behavior in the way that switch works. To avoid any confusion, we’re going to create a new external switch, and a new private switch. 

1. With New virtual network switch selected on the left, and External selected on the right, click Create Virtual Switch.  
2. Give your new virtual switch a name, I generally use the naming convention of HV- purpose (External, Internal, Private) \- SW0 then what number the switch is. If I have two private virtual switches they would be 01 and 02\.   
3. Enter any notes about your virtual switch, I don’t really have any notes I want to add at the moment.  
4. If your computer has more than one network card, you’re going to want to select one that has an existing outside connection. That would all depend on your current configuration.   
5. We don’t really have any use for the VLAN ID right now. But if the network card we used was connected to a physical switch that was in trunk mode in Cisco terms. We could assign a VLAN ID here and every virtual machine that used this switch would be part of the same VLAN. Most likely though, you’ll leave this unconfigured and assign a VLAN ID on the virtual machines. This would be similar to using port lever VLAN assignment on a managed switch. That’s a little outside the scope of this course, however, I can certainly expand upon that if there are enough student requests.   
6. Click Apply and our new external switch is created. 

Now for the Private switch. Unlike the External switch which allows the virtual machine to communicate with devices beyond the local host, a private switch only allows VMs to talk to other VMs on the local host. In a lab environment, you might not want your VMs to talk to the local host or anything except your other lab VMs. If you’re building a lab that has a DHCP server, you would most certainly want to keep THAT off your normal network, to prevent it trying to give out IP addresses to production clients. This could cause you all sorts of problems from calls that people can’t access the Internet to loss of connectivity to network drives. Then you might get to explain to the network guy or a supervisor what an unauthorized DHCP was doing on the network, if you managed this in a work environment. Not a conversation you want to have, believe me. 

	Even though we’re going to have our VMs on our Private virtual switch in the future, we’re going to have to connect them using the External switch to start with. But, we’ll get to that when the time comes. 

To create our private virtual switch we’re going to perform a very similar process to the one we used to create our external switch.

1. With New virtual network switch selected on the left, and Private selected on the right, click Create Virtual Switch.  
2. Give your new virtual switch a name, I generally use the naming convention of HV- purpose (External, Internal, Private) \- SW0 then what number the switch is. If I have two private virtual switches they would be 01 and 02\. This one is going to be HV-Private-SW01.  
3. Enter any notes about your virtual switch, again I don’t really have any notes I want to add at the moment.  
4. For a private switch, we don’t have to worry about the underlying physical network card.   
5. Once again, we’re not going to assign the switch a VLAN ID, we’re going to do that at the virtual computer level.   
6. Click Apply and our new private switch is created. 

## **Building the Lab** {#building-the-lab-1}

Building the VMs for the labs is pretty straight forward, however, I’m going to cover it in the interest of completeness. Feel free to skip this section if you feel the desire to do so.

### **Creating virtual drives** {#creating-virtual-drives}

	I like to create the virtual drives before I create the virtual machine that’s going to use them. I could create them at the same time but that doesn’t give me all the options I want when creating a virtual disk. Mainly, I don’t get the option to use a dynamically expanding or differencing disk. Creating the virtual drive when creating the virtual machine will default it to a dynamically expanding drive, which is not exactly what I want in all cases.  
	When creating virtual disks for production VMs, I generally create fixed disks to avoid running out of physical disk space on the host as the drive expands during use. I’ve seen too many clients run themselves out of actual disk space because they only saw the space the the virtual reported was available on the virtual drive and never think about the underlying storage capacity. So to avoid that I’ve just gotten in the habit of creating fixed disks on production VMs. Avoiding the panicked call from clients that their VMs won’t spin up. 

#### How-To {#how-to}

With the Hyper-V Manager open, right-click on the local computer name, and select **New** |  **Hard Disk…**  
![][image5]

Complete the New Virtual Hard Disk Wizard with answers to fit your needs. 

![][image6]

Generally you’ll leave the format as VHDX, unless you have a reason for using the older VHD, or the VHD set format. Since we don’t really have a use for either of those formats in this course, we’ll be sticking with VHDX.

![][image7]

	Now we need to define the type of disk we want to use. As I said before, for most production VMs I create, I use “Fixed size” so the size of the virtual drive is allocated at creation which generally keeps people from using all the available physical space on the host later on.   
	I’m going to use both dynamically expanding and differencing disks in this course for a couple of reasons. 

1. One, we shouldn’t be getting anywhere close to using the full capacity of the virtual drives.   
2. Second, using differencing disks will save time when spinning up new virtual machines as we go along. Differencing disks also save us some drive space, but that’s not the primary reason we’re going to use them. If you’re ever asked on a Microsoft exam how to save disk space when using VMs, the answer is to use differencing disks.

   
	The master plan in creating the lab is to use “master” virtual machines that have the initial operating system installation on them, so I only have to go through the OS installation once per operating system (2012, 2016, and Windows 10). I’ll note when I’m using a differencing disk when creating the new virtual drive for a machine.

![][image8]

	When naming virtual disks, I like to use the name of the VM it's going to be attached to and underscore drive letter. This first disk will be used in the Server 2012 Master VM and will be drive letter C. So I’ll name the drive ***2012-Master\_C***. I realize that everyone has their own naming scheme that makes sense to them, so feel free to use whatever makes sense to you. I do it this way because it’s pretty obvious what VM and what drive the file is for. 

	![][image9]

	When it comes to sizing the virtual drive, everyone has their own way to doing it. Personally, I like to keep the OS partition pretty small. Just big enough to hold the OS with a little room to spare for things like Windows temp files and so on. I prefer to keep the OS and data on seperate drives and disks when possible but, that’s more a carry over from my early days in IT. Plus it gives me the ability to still get to data, should the primary drive be rendered unusable. Say our C drive virtual drive file gets corrupted for some strange reason. If we also kept our application or user data on that same file, we’d be in a real fix and be in full on panic mode trying to recover that file. But, if we stored that same information on another virtual drive file, we could just attach it to a new VM and be back up with access to our data that much faster. Sure, it’s a simple example and I hope you would already have contingency plans in place to recover corrupted drive files, but being able to attach data storage to different VMs makes things like upgrading the OS that much easier in the future as well. But we’ll get to that later. For now, I’m going to keep the default 127GB. Again, configure it as needed for your environment.  
	  
	![][image10]

	The final screen of the wizard gives us a summary of the options we’ve chosen. I recommend you always pause and look it over, even in development virtual environments. Getting used to looking at this screen over and comparing it to your design notes will help you avoid lost time having to recreate file later because you did something simple like forget to make the drive 200GB instead of 127GB or any number of configuration mistakes. I’ve made plenty of the years because I go in a rush and didn’t make time to pause and look over what I was about to do. Of course, I usually figure out my mistake AFTER I’ve starting installing the OS or something. That’s just how I roll from time to time. 

#### Challenge {#challenge}

In this challenge, I want you to create a new virtual disk for our Windows 10 machines. 

### **Creating Virtual Machine** {#creating-virtual-machine}

	Now that we have our virtual disks, we need to create the virtual machines that will leverage those disks. With the Hyper-V Manager open, right-click on the local computer name and select **New** | **Virtual Machine…**.

	![][image11]

	Click Next to get past the Before you Begin screen, you can always click Do not show this page again to avoid seeing it in the future, which for some reason I never do. No reason why that I know of, I just forget to do it. 

	![][image12]

	With the Before you Begin screen bypassed, we now have to give a name to our new virtual machine. For my non-production virtual environments where I’m mixing different OS versions, I like to use a naming scheme that lets me know the OS version and the role the machine is playing in the environment. This machine will be my 2012 Master machine that holds my initial Server 2012 installation, so I’ll name it 2012-Master. I am using Server 2012 R2, so something like 2012R2-Master might make more sense, but as I will not have any plain 2012 machines on the network, I’ll save the typing since any 2012 machine will be R2. 

	![][image13]

The next screen is where we choose what generation VM we want. Generation 2 uses UEFI instead of the traditional BIOS, as well as synthetic hardware as opposed to emulated hardware. I’m not going to go too far down the rabbit hole on this, as this course is about Server administration, but given that we don’t have any legacy requirements, I’m going to choose generation 2\. 

	![][image14]

Next up, we choose the amount of startup memory and whether or not to use dynamic memory for the VM. As the name suggests, startup RAM is the amount of RAM the system will have at startup and is the minimum amount of RAM that VM will ever have. Dynamic Memory allows the system to adjust the amount of RAM the system has as needed. If the machine needs more RAM, Hyper-V can give the system more RAM. As the system needs less RAM, it can drop the RAM back to the startup level. I usually set every VM to start with 1 GB (1024) of RAM, and turn dynamic memory on.  
	![][image15]

	In the configuring networking section, we need to set the VM to use the virtual switch we want. For our purposes, the Default switch will work just fine. 

	![][image16]

	The next screen is where we get to tell our new VM to use that virtual disk we created earlier. Just choose “Use an existing virtual hard disk”, click browse and select the VHDX we created earlier. 

	![][image17]

Lastly, we arrive at the summary screen, I strongly suggest you pause when you get to this screen and carefully look it over to verify that you have everything set the way you want. It’s a little annoying when you have to go back and create things all over again because you set something wrong in a rush. 

![][image18]

Click Finish and you’ll see you new new VM in the Hyper-V Manager window ready and waiting. Before we turn it on though, we are going to make a couple changes to the settings. 

The first change I’m going to make is to turn off checkpoints. There’s not much need for them in the lab we’re creating. However, if you want them on, please leave them on. I turn them off as a preference.   
After disabling checkpoints, I’m going to ensure that the system gets it 1GB of RAM by checking the memory settings. Even though we gave the VM 1GB of startup memory, Hyper-V still sets the minimum to 512 for dynamic memory. That would override the 1GB setting so the system would try to keep its memory needs below the 512 mark. I’m going to enter 1024 in the minimum RAM field to make sure the system always has at least the 1GB of RAM I want it to have.  
In the integration services section, I’m going to turn off time synchronization. This is a must for domain controllers as it avoids circular time referencing where the VM is pulling time from the host, and the host is pulling time from the VM, and things get out of control.   
Finally, I’m going to add a DVD drive and attach my Server 2012 ISO image to it so I can start the installation when I fire it up. Click Apply and/or OK and we’re ready to load this thing up.

### **Installing Server 2016** {#installing-server-2016}

	The process for installing Microsoft operating systems is pretty much the same no matter what version you’re dealing with. If you’re building the lab to work along with me on this course, you’ll get a double dose of how-to install the two versions of Server we’re going to deal with. I figure you’re probably already familiar with how to install Microsoft server and Windows 10, I include these sections for completeness, if you’re comfortable with installing the operating systems, feel free to skip this part.  
When you boot a computer for the first time, the installation process with ask you the basic questions of what language, time and currency format, and keyboard language. For me, the English US defaults are fine. 

![][image19]

Clicking next takes us to the next screen where we only have 2 options. We can either install the OS now, or repair our computer. Seeing as there’s nothing on it, repairing is obviously out. 

![][image20]

Now we get to choose which version we want to install. Do we want Standard or DataCenter, and do we want a graphical interface or not? For this course, I will be using Standard core installations. I’ve made it a point to try getting my clients away from remotely connecting to servers to do things like add users to AD. I’ve been getting them used to using the Remote Server Administration Tools (RSAT) and managing their servers from their workstation. This helps prevent forgetting which machine you’re currently working with and clicking on something that ends up breaking your network. Over the years I’ve seen people use all sorts of methods to keep track of what machine they’re currently working on. I’ve seen different color backgrounds, to text on the background with the machine name and IP. Those are all good and well, until you have a window full screen and can’t see the background anymore.   
I prefer never directly connecting to servers if I can use remote management tools. I prefer the extra layer of isolation from the server and the decreased likelihood I’ll blow up a server. So, unlike almost every book or course I’ve seen since Server 2008, we’re going to be using core installations for our servers, where I can. There are some roles that still require us to have a graphical interface on the server, should we run across one of those cases, I’ll install the GUI.

### **Configuring our Server 2012 R2 Master VM** {#configuring-our-server-2012-r2-master-vm}

Once the installation is complete, we should be staring at the login screen for our Server 2012 master machine. From there we’ll get logged in and start our configuration, then sysprep it so it serves as our master image.

![][image26]

When we send the Ctrl+Alt+Delete to the machine (which can sent using  Ctrl+Alt+End, or clicking on Action | Ctrl+Alt+Delete on the VM’s window), we’re given the option log on using the Administrator account. 

![][image27]

Clicking on Administrator will prompt us to change the Administrator’s password.

.![][image28]

Click Ok, then enter the password of your choice in the New Password and Confirm Password fields, then click the arrow in the Confirm Password box to log in.

![][image29]

You should see the message telling the password has been changed.

![][image30]

## **Gotcha\!\! The InterfaceIndex and Index\# of network interfaces** {#gotcha!!-the-interfaceindex-and-index#-of-network-interfaces}

	At some point  you’re bound to run into the dreaded InterfaceIndex and Index\# of your network interfaces. This can be a major source of confusion if \- like me \- you sometimes fail to grasp the obvious. Depending on where you’re looking, you might see the Index\# or the InterfaceIndex. Where this can get you into trouble is when \- again like me \- you incorrectly assume they are the same number. Which will result you in scratching your head as you try to figure out why your PowerShell commands are giving you ugly red text errors.  
	If you go from the number given in the network settings of the sconfig menu, then you’ll get the Index\#. So you’ll incorrectly think that’s the number you need to give the PowerShell command. When in reality, what you’re needing to pass is the InterfaceIndex. “So how the hell do I find that, you ask? The InterfaceIndex is part of the information you get from several commands. NetSH, WMI, and PowerShell give you the InterfaceIndex without much trouble. Creating the lab domain

![][image48]

![][image49]

Press 7 then Enter to bring up the Remote Desktop options. You’re presented with **`(E)nable or (D)isable Remote Desktop? (Blank=Cancel)`**, press E to enable remote desktop. Next you’re asked how secure you want to make remote desktop. By choosing the more secure option, you’re requiring clients to have Network Level Authentication, the other option lets any version of remote desktop to connect. Since we want our domain to be secure in the lab, and in real life, we’re going to use the more secure option. Enter 1, and press the Enter key. The InterfaceIndex though, is something we need to find before we can issue the command. 

Here’s where things can get a little confusing. There are two index numbers that Microsoft assigns a network card, the Interface Index and the Index\#. 

*The different numbers are probably the difference between Index and InterfaceIndex. Those are different numbers. The Index is stable and more reliable between restarts. The InterfaceIndex is the easier number to get and matches the Interface shown if you do a "route print" command.*

Once the File Server is rebooted, we’re going to add the File Server role to it. We can add this either through PowerShell or via GUI on our Windows 10 management workstation. I’m going to use the GUI, but feel free to use PowerShell, if you prefer.

When we were creating the virtual disks for the file server, I created a second disk to function and the D drive for holding the shares as I wanted that to be stored on a drive other than the one hosting the operating system. We need to ensure that the disk is active and ready for us to create shares when the time comes. 

In the server manager of our management workstation, we can see what disks are currently on all our servers. You’ll notice there’s a disk 0 and disk 1 on 2012-FS01. Disk 0 is where our C drive lives, and disk 1 is where we’re going to store all that share data. We can see the status of the drive is online, does that mean the disk is all configured? 

The answer is no, the disk still needs some configuring before we have a fully operable drive to work with. I’m guessing you already know what a partition is, so I’m going to skip over that explanation. If you guys want me to go into detail about that, send me a message on the class board and I’ll add that in.

If we click on disk 0, we can see that the C drive (or volume) lives there. Clicking on disk 1 shows there are currently no volumes on the drive. Also, note that the partition information shows as “Unknown”. That would be because we have no created a partition on the drive, or any volumes for that matter. Let’s right-click on disk 1 and see what options we have available to us. While there are a few options here, we’re really only interested in 2, “New Volume”, and “Initialize”. Before Windows will see a disk it has to be online and initialized. Let’s initialize the disk now. We can see that the partition information has changed and now shows GPT, right-clicking on the disk reveals that the initialize option is gone, so the disk has been initialized. Can you guess what option we’re going to use next? If you guessed “New Volume”, you’d be right. We obviously don’t want to take the disk offline because we want to use it, and we certainly don’t want to reset the disk. Clicking on “New Volume” opens the New Volume Wizard and walks us through the process of creating a new volume. Ah, but there’s a problem. The first drive letter I can assign to the new volume is E, I want it to be D. But what happened to the D option? Windows automatically assigned D to the DVD drive that’s part of our virtual machine. Let’s fix that up so my OCD doesn’t freak out when I create the volume. Start by canceling the wizard.   
Now let’s open Computer Management and connect to 2012-FS01 so we can have a look at the full disk management of FS01. 

![][image59]

What’s with *this* error? We have remote management enabled, we’re using an administrative account \- actually the all powerful admin account \- on a domain joined computer. We shouldn’t be getting this error, we are ALL powerful...right? 

	While we are ALL powerful, this error is actually about the firewall blocking some of the services we need in order to remotely look at the disk management in this way. We’re going to have to punch a few holes in the firewall to get to what we want. 

On the Windows 10 workstation, we’re going to enter a remote PowerShell session using the Enter-PSSession 2012-FS01 command. Once our remote PowerShell session is ready we’re going to enter in the following command.

**`Enable-NetFirewallRule -DisplayGroup “Remote Volume Management”`**  
**`Enable-NetFirewallRule -DisplayGroup "Remote Event Log Management"`**

On Mgmt Workstation  
**`Enable-NetFirewallRule -DisplayGroup “Remote Volume Management”`**

Now, let’s try that again.   
And...now we can load up the disk management remotely on FS01.

We can see that the DVD-ROM is assigned drive letter D, which we don’t want. Let’s assign that drive letter E. 

When we go back to the Server Manager and refresh, then open the New Volume Wizard again, we should now be able to assign drive letter D to the new volume. Once we’ve created the volume and assigned it drive letter D we can create the home folder for our users.

Ideally, we’d have things broken up into multiple domains but I decided not to over complicate things while keeping in the theme of the lab. We’re going to create an Organizational Unit (OU) named ***Galactic Republic*** that will hold all our user and device information. In that Galactic Republic OU, we’ll create OU’s for the Jedi, Senators, and IT staff. I’ve already created the PowerShell script and comma separated (CSV) file to save you the mundane task of creating them all manually, plus we’ll learn more about managing AD with PowerShell, something that will save you a lot of time in the real world.

Of course, when we do this the first time we’re going to get yelled at and told that running scripts is currently disabled. So let’s fix that. ## **Home Folder Share permissions** {#home-folder-share-permissions}

	When creating the shares for the user’s home folders, we have to adjust the NTFS permissions to prevent other users from being able to see what’s in other people’s folders. When we created the shares the default permissions inherited will give everyone the ability to go into everyone else’s folders, and that is something we do not want.   
	I’ve seen this a lot of client environments, and most of the time the users have no idea because they’re not navigating to what should be a hidden share directly. They’re generally only clicking on the drive letter assigned and going to their own folder. But all it takes if that one person who knows how to get to the share directly to cause havoc on the system. You don’t want to be the system administrator *after* a security hole like this is exposed.   
	To prevent users from getting to other user’s folders and to save us from having to remember to change the permissions every time we create a new user, we’re going to change the permissions on the root share for the user’s home folders. We’re going to make several changes.

### **Share permissions** {#share-permissions}

While you can get away with leaving the default of *Everyone* having full control to the share, I’ve been in the habit of removing the everyone group from most things and using the *Authenticated Users* group. This is more a carry over from the days when the *Everyone* group included both the anonymous and guest users, which is no longer the case. But old habits die hard for me. The following table is how my share permissions are going to look.   
You can leave the everyone group with full control and you’ll be fine, the “old school” admin in me just can’t do that. Also, there isn’t a whole lot of difference between full control and change permissions for our purposes, but giving users full control to a share just makes my head hurt. 

| Group | Permissions |
| :---- | :---- |
| Authenticated Users | Change |
| Domain Admins | Full Control |

### **NTFS permissions** {#ntfs-permissions}

Now that I have my share permissions properly set so as not to offend my OCD, I’m going to change the NTFS permissions so that users only have access to their folder. This will also prevent users from being able to navigate directly to the hidden share, unless they have permission to do so.   
I’m going to start by disabling inheritance, and converting them into explicit permissions. Next, I’m going to do is remove *Users (\<server name\>\\Users)* group from the Access Control List (ACL). Then I’m going to set the remaining permissions per the following table.

| Group | Permission(s) | Applies To |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Domain Admins | Full Control | This folder, subfolders, and files. |
| Creator Owner | Full Control | Subfolders and files only. |
| System | Full Control | This folder, subfolders, and files. |
| Authenticated Users | Create Folders / Append Data List Folder / Read Data Read Attributes Traverse Folder / Execute File |  This Folder Only |

Now when we log in as a normal user, we can see that we have access to our home folder, but cannot get directly to the share, or to anyone else’s folders. 

## **Senate Shares** {#senate-shares}

The share for Senate users requires us to do a little more configuring of the NTFS permissions. With the ***Server Manager*** open, we’re going to navigate to the ***Shares*** management. Click on *File and Storage Services* in the left pane. Next click on *Shares* in what I’m going to call the middle pane. Right-click on the *Senate Shares* and select properties. Select *Permissions*, then click the *Customize Permissions* button.

![][image60]

### **Share Permissions** {#share-permissions-1}

Selecting the Share tab will let us customize the share permissions. Seeing as we don’t want just any user to be able to access the share, we’re going to give only the dl.Senators, and dl.Senate Staff groups change permissions. The Domain Admins group will get full control.

| Group | Permissions |
| :---- | :---- |
| Senators | Change |
| Senate Staff | Change |
| Domain Admins | Full Control |

### **NTFS Permissions** {#ntfs-permissions-1}

The NTFS permissions require a little more adjustment to allow the Senate Staff the ability to add files, and folders. But we want them only to be able to delete that they out on the share. While Senators have the ability to add, create, and delete anything in their folder(s), but can only create folders in the Senate Shares folder.

#### Senate Share NTFS {#senate-share-ntfs}

	Of course, the first step is to disable inheritance and remove the local server Users permissions.

| Group | Permission(s) | Applies To |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Domain Admins | Full Control | This folder, subfolders, and files. |
| Creator Owner | Full Control | Subfolders and files only. |
| System | Full Control | This folder, subfolders, and files. |
| Authenticated Users | Create Folders / Append Data List Folder / Read Data Read Attributes Traverse Folder / Execute File |  This Folder Only |

# **Installing Windows Server 2016** {#installing-windows-server-2016}

## **Type of Installation** {#type-of-installation}

### **Server Core** {#server-core}

Server Core is the bare-bones installation option. It has no graphical interface to work with, any local interaction must be done through the command line or PowerShell. Graphical tools can be used on a Core installation, but must be used from a remote computer that has a graphical interface, such as Windows 10\.

Server Core installations support the following roles

* Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS)  
* Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS)  
* Active Directory Federation Services (AD FS)  
* Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services (AD LDS)  
* Active Directory Rights Management Services (AD RMS)  
* DHCP Server  
* DNS Server  
* Fax Server  
* File and Storage Services  
* BITS Server  
* BranchCache  
* Hyper-V  
* Network Policy and Access Services  
* Print and Document Services  
* Remote Access  
* Remote Desktop Services  
* Volume Activation Services  
* Web Server (IIS)  
* Windows Deployment Services  
* .NET Framework 3.5 features  
* .NET Framework 4.6 features  
* Streaming Media Services  
* Failover Clustering  
* iSCSI  
* Network Load Balancing  
* MPIO  
* qWave  
* Telnet Server/Client  
* Windows Server Migration Tools  
* Windows PowerShell 4.0

### **Why use Core?** {#why-use-core?}

The primary reason to use Server Core is to free up system resources from managing a graphical interface that is hardly used. In almost every environment I’ve worked in, we’ve installed a server in the server room managed it through Remote Desktop. Meaning that the system wasted resources on the GUI that was hardly ever accessed.   
We can do the same thing using the Remote Server Administration tools and directly connect to the server.

# **Active Directory** {#active-directory}

## **Delegate Control** {#delegate-control}

Using the principle of least privilege (POLP), users, and administrators should only have the permissions needed to perform their job functions. We therefore do not want to give every server administrator the same permissions that come with the built-in administrator user. We do ,however, want to ensure they can do things like create/delete users and reset passwords without having to log in with a different account. We want to provide layers of security, but not in such a way as the process becomes cumbersome to use.   
That’s where Delegate Control comes in. We can assign permissions to users, and groups to allow them to perform needed functions without giving them more privileges than they need. For example, we can assign out helpdesk personnel the right to reset passwords, and only password. We can also limit the OUs they can reset the passwords for. We wouldn’t want the average helpdesk employee to be able to reset the Chancellor’s password now would we?

### **Verifying Delegate Control Permissions** {#verifying-delegate-control-permissions}

There are a couple of ways to check what permissions users/groups have. The first is dsacls.exe, which can run from a workstation that has the Remote Server Administration Tools (RSAT) installed. Powershell can also be used by leveraging the Get-Acl cmdlet, and using Active Directory as the “drive”. However, using the Get-Acl cmdlet does require some massaging to get it to display useful information. You can download a script from the Technet gallery, if you want to look into that more on your own ([https://gallery.technet.microsoft.com/Active-Directory-OU-1d09f989](https://gallery.technet.microsoft.com/Active-Directory-OU-1d09f989)). I’m going to stick with dsacls.exe for simplicity and ease of use. 

*Sample dsacls.exe*   
dsacls "ou=it,ou=galactic republic,dc=republic,dc=example,dc=org" \>\> C:\\tmp\\ACL-Results.log

*Sample Powershell Get-Acl*  
(Get-Acl \-Path "AD:\\ou=it,ou=galactic republic,dc=republic,dc=example,dc=or  
g").access | Where {$\_.IdentityReference \-like "republic\\republic.Admins"} | Select IdentityReference,ObjectType,AccessControlType

## **Setting up DFS Namespaces and Folders** {#setting-up-dfs-namespaces-and-folders}

1) Create *DFS Shortcuts* folder on D:\\.  
2) Create *Home Folders* folder in *DFS Shortcuts*.  
3) Share this folder with the share name *Home Folders*. (Detail how-to)  
4) Create *Home Folders* folder on D:\\.  
5) Share this folder with the share name *Home Folders Data*.  
   1) Share permissions:  
      1) Remove *Everyone*  
      2) Domain Users \- Change  
      3) Domain Admins \- Full Control  
      4) System \- Full Control  
   2) NTFS permissions  
      1) Disable inheritance, convert inherited permissions into explicit permissions.  
      2) Delete the \\\\\<server name\>\\users from the ACL  
      3) Add *Domain Users* \- Full Control \[This folder, subfolders, and files\]  
      4) Add *Domain Users* \- Traverse folder, List folder, read attributes, read extended attributes, create folders, read permissions \[This folder only\]  
      5) Leave *Administrators*, *SYSTEM*, and *CREATOR OWNER* as is.  
6) Create new folder in *D:\\Home Folders* named *Staff*.

### **In DFS Management** {#in-dfs-management}

7) Create namespace called *Home Folders*.  
   1) In Edit settings change *C:\\DFSRoots\\Temp* to *D:\\DFS Shortcuts\\Home Folders*.  
   2) Leave shared folder permissions at default.  
8) Add a new folder to the *Home Folders* namespace  
   1) Set the folder name to *Staff*.  
   2) Set the target to the *Staff* folder in the *Home Folder Data* share.  
9) Once the folder has been added, we should see the shortcut icon in the *D:\\DFS Shortcuts\\Home Folders* folder.
